    description: `The Gangabal Twin Lakes trek leads to two sacred high-altitude lakes — Gangabal and Nundkol — set at 3,586 metres beneath the northern face of Harmukh peak (4,501 m), one of Kashmir's most sacred mountains. The lakes are revered in Hindu tradition as the source of the Ganges, and the annual Gangabal mela draws pilgrims alongside trekkers. The route from Naranag (the end point of the Kashmir Great Lakes trek) climbs through dense conifer forest to open alpine meadows and the twin lakes, whose cobalt blue is intense against the white snowfields of Harmukh. A shorter and less-crowded alternative to the Great Lakes circuit, the Gangabal approach from Naranag is a superb 3–4 day moderate trek.`,
